<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-219-054  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 219 054.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  March 5 1990 v11 n10 p18(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big isn't always best. (selecting an accountingsystem)(Peer-to-Peer) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Serrett-Curran; Schnuer, Avner.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer purchasing decisions frequently have as much to do withthe vendor's reputation or financial stability as with the meritsof the equipment itself, but the needs for a quality product andfor stable support services occasionally conflict.andP;  A case studyof an accounting-system purchase at Elscint Inc is presented.andO;Elscint, a wholly owned subsidiary of Elscint Ltd in Israel thatmanufactures medical scanning equipment, had outgrown its Lawsonmainframe-based accounting system and needed software that wouldrun on its DEC VAX 3800 systems.andP;  Requirements includedintercompany capabilities, microcomputer-to-mainframeconnectivity, and the ability to produce reports at any time.andO;Proposed systems were narrowed down to two, one of which came fromthe VAX market leader.andP;  The other was Coda Inc's IntegratedAccounting System, but Coda is a small, relatively new company.andO;Concerns about its stability made Elscint nervous, but a supportguarantee led the firm to implement IAS, a decision that wasvalidated by subsequent events.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Management of EDPSystem SelectionDecision MakingEquipment AcquisitionVendor RelationsCase StudyAccounting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>